03718nam a22004935i 9780300148244DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20082008ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001482447 a10.12987/97803001482442doi  a(DE-B1597)485147  a(OCoLC)1024045098  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a813.541 aKhrushcheva, Nina L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImagining Nabokov :bRussia Between Art and Politics /cNina L. Khrushcheva. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Transliteration and Translations -- tList of Abbreviations -- tChronology -- tIntroduction: Nabokov and Us -- tPrologue: Nabokov's Russian Return . . . and Retreat -- tOne. Imagining Nabokov -- tTwo. On the Way to the Author -- tThree. Poet, Genius, and Hero -- tEpilogue: Nabokov as the Pushkin of the Twenty-first Century -- tThe End -- tEnvoi -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aVladimir Nabokov's "Western choice"-his exile to the West after the 1917 Bolshevik Revolution-allowed him to take a crucial literary journey, leaving the closed nineteenth-century Russian culture behind and arriving in the extreme openness of twentieth-century America. In Imagining Nabokov: Russia Between Art and Politics, Nina L. Khrushcheva offers the novel hypothesis that because of this journey, the works of Russian-turned-American Vladimir Nabokov (1899-1977) are highly relevant to the political transformation under way in Russia today. Khrushcheva, a Russian living in America, finds in Nabokov's novels a useful guide for Russia's integration into the globalized world. Now one of Nabokov's "Western" characters herself, she discusses the cultural and social realities of contemporary Russia that he foresaw a half-century earlier. In Pale Fire; Ada, or Ardor; Pnin; and other works, Nabokov reinterpreted the traditions of Russian fiction, shifting emphasis from personal misery and communal life to the notion of forging one's own "happy" destiny. In the twenty-first century Russia faces a similar challenge, Khrushcheva contends, and Nabokov's work reveals how skills may be acquired to cope with the advent of democracy, capitalism, and open borders.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300148244423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300148244.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles